<DOC><DOCNO> AP881017-0269 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-88 1511EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     10-17 0284</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0299</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Stock prices showed a modest gain in quiettrading today, aided by new evidence of a slowing economy.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 8.18 to 2,141.36 by3 p.m. on Wall Street.   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in nationwide trading of NewYork Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 730 up, 664 down and 531unchanged.   Analysts said traders took a generally upbeat view of thecurrent state of the economy, believing that growth has slowed oflate to a steady, sustainable pace.   Those hopes drew some fresh support from government statisticsissued this morning that showed a drop in capacity use in September.   But inflation worries haven't been entirely snuffed out on WallStreet, and brokers said investors were looking ahead warily toFriday's scheduled report on the consumer price index for September.   Furthermore, just about all market-watchers agree, stocks arelikely to be a tough product to sell all week with the anniversaryWednesday of last fall's crash, and all the attendant publicity.   Hospital Corp. of America rose { to 48} in active trading. Aspecial committee of outside directors rejected a $51-a-sharebuyout bid by management, asserting that there were other partiesthat might be willing to make a higher offer.   Other gains among the volume leaders included Chrysler, up } at26[; International Business Machines, up 1| at 121], and AmericanTelephone andamp; Telegraph, up [ at 26}.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose.47 to 155.93. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex was up .57 at 303.12.   Volume on the Big Board came to 99.37 million shares with anhour to go.</TEXT></DOC>